article.description: Sam Cassell made five free throws in the final 18 seconds of overtime Saturday night to lead the Milwaukee Bucks to a 138-133 comeback victory over the Golden State Warriors.
article.headline: Payton's 3 at buzzer, Cassell's FTs lead to victory
article.linkText: Bucks outlast Warriors in wild OT shootout
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Two of the NBA's top offensive teams did what they do best Saturday night.
Payton

Cassell

Sam Cassell made five free throws in the final 18 seconds of overtime to lead the Milwaukee Bucks to a 138-133 comeback victory over the Golden State Warriors. "Good ol' ABA-style basketball,'' Milwaukee coach George Karl said, referring to the defunct league of a quarter century ago that featured wild, high-scoring games. Golden State made 24 of its first 32 shots in the second half and led 104-88 with 9:38 left. The Bucks then used a 26-11 run to cut the Warriors' lead to 115-114 on Gary Payton's 3-pointer with 2:31 left. Payton made a 3-pointer with 3.4 seconds left to force overtime. "Me and Sam (Cassell) had eye contact, and he told me to kick out,'' said Payton, who scored 28 points, his most since joining Milwaukee nine games ago. "Toni (Kukoc) set the pick and I got a good look.'' Cassell finished with 28 points and 13 assists. Golden State is third in the NBA in scoring at 101 points a game, but is 28th in defense, giving up 101.4 a game. "We just gave up,'' guard Jason Richardson said. "I really thought we did. We just stopped playing defense and I think we celebrated a little bit too early because we were up so much.'' The Bucks, fifth in the NBA at 98.5 points a game, shot 7-of-10 on 3-pointers in the fourth quarter, outscoring Golden State 41-29 in the period. "It's kind of funny, I always felt we had a chance to win it,'' said Karl, who played in the ABA for San Antonio in the mid-1970s. "I thought we'd do it with a little more defense instead of making six or seven 3s.'' Golden State made 56 percent of its shots in regulation, but only two of nine shots in overtime. "We stepped up to play at the end,'' said Michael Redd, who had 16 of his 22 points in the fourth quarter. Cassell was fouled with 18 seconds left and made the first free throw for a 132-130 lead. He missed the second free throw, but Kukoc grabbed the rebound and passed to Cassell, who was fouled again. He made both free throws for a 134-130 lead. Gilbert Arenas made one free throw with 10 seconds to go, and Tim Thomas scored on a fast-break layup with 6.2 seconds left for a 136-131 lead. Antawn Jamison led Golden State with 40 points. With the score tied at 119 in regulation, 5-5 Earl Boykins drove the lane on Cassell, turned and scored on a jumper to give the Warriors a 121-119 lead. After a timeout, Payton's turnaround 5-footer missed and Jamison grabbed the rebound, was fouled and made one free throw with 9.8 seconds left for a 122-119 lead. Redd's 3-pointer missed, but Milwaukee kept possession and Payton hit an open 3-pointer to tie it at 122 with 3.4 seconds to go. Gilbert Arenas scored 30 points and Troy Murphy had a career-high 22 rebounds for Golden State. The Warriors have lost two consecutive games after winning six straight. They have lost seven in a row to Milwaukee over four seasons. The Bucks are 5-5 since trading Ray Allen, Kevin Ollie and Ronald Murray to Seattle for Gary Payton and Desmond Mason, and are 5-4 with Payton and Mason in the lineup.

Game notes
Warriors F Danny Fortson missed his third consecutive game due to a death in his family. ... It was Milwaukee's fourth game in five nights. The Bucks went 3-1 during the stretch. ... The Bucks have won 18 of their last 21 against Golden State in Milwaukee. ... Milwaukee is 4-3 in overtime and Golden State is 1-2.
